      "content": [
        {
          "text": "# `*State` vs `*const State`\n\n**`*State`** — mutable pointer. Callee may write through it.\n**`*const State`** — read-only pointer. Callee may only read.\n\nIn C ABI, both are just `State*` at the machine level (a pointer is a pointer; `const` is a compile-time contract, not a runtime difference). The two map to:\n\n- `*State` → `State*`\n- `*const State` → `const State*`\n\n## Which is correct here\n\n`lex_state_init` **writes** to the memory (`state_pointer.* = .{...}`). It must be `*State`. Using `*const State` would be a compile error in Zig because you cannot assign through a const pointer.\n\nThe same applies to `lex_add` — it mutates the state, so `*State` is required.\n\n`*const State` would only be appropriate for a read-only function, e.g. a hypothetical `lex_state_get_length(state: *const State) u8`. Using `const` there documents intent to the C caller (header would show `const State*`) and lets the compiler catch accidental writes.\n\n## Rule of thumb for FFI\n\n- Mutates the pointee → `*T` (C: `T*`)\n- Reads only → `*const T` (C: `const T*`)\n\nSo your current `*State` is correct. Don't change it.",
